<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: More Brazilian iron ore deals
agreed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BILL HINCHBERGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRAZIL'S Companhia Vale do Rio Doce, the world's leading exporter of iron
ore, has reached an agreement that will cut the price paid by Japanese steel
mills by between 11 and 12 per cent.
Japan is the largest market for the state-owned company's ore production,
accounting for about 19m tonnes of the company's 60.4m tonnes of exports
last year. The price reductions are similar in scale to those contained in
an agreement with German producers announced last week. The company
suggested that they would set the pattern for its prices for the rest of
Europe.
High grade northern sinter material, from the Carajas site, will be supplied
at Dollars 18.15 a tonne and southern sinter at Dollars 16.90 a tonne.
Prices for pellets will be renegotiated under a separate accord. The German
deal included a price reduction for pellets from Dollars 31 to Dollars 28 a
tonne.
CVRD's existing contract with the Japanese mills will remain in effect until
its scheduled expiry in April. A company official said that the early
renegotiation was 'completely atypical'.
The company also revealed that producers in the UK and Italy will enjoy
similar price reductions.
