<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / International Company News: Strong final quarter lifts
Primerica to Dollars 593m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRIMERICA, the diversified US financial services group, yesterday announced
a 16 per cent increase in fourth-quarter profits to Dollars 153.3m, in spite
of a decline in brokerage earnings.
The strong final quarter took Primerica's full-year 1992 profits to Dollars
593m, a 24 per cent improvement on the Dollars 478.8m earned in 1991.
A net gain of Dollars 68m from the sale of securities holdings and other
assets, combined with lower debt costs and solid increases in profits at
Primerica's consumer finance and insurance services divisions, helped to
offset the drop in net income at the group's Smith Barney stockbroking unit.
Smith Barney reported a profit of Dollars 38.2m in the final quarter, down
from Dollars 49.8m a year earlier.
The decline in earnings was attributed to lower trading revenues, the result
of market conditions that were less favourable than in the fourth quarter of
1991, which was a particularly strong period for US equity markets.
Although profits tailed off in the final quarter, Smith Barney still
produced record earnings of Dollars 170.1m for the full year, well up on the
previous high of Dollars 152.4m reported in 1991.
Large increases in broking, investment banking and asset management revenues
were behind the record performance.
Elsewhere in the Primerica group, earnings were higher than a year ago.
Consumer finance services recorded net income of Dollars 51.3m in the fourth
quarter, up 13 per cent on the same period a year earlier and once again the
result of cost containment measures and lower loan loss provisions.
Full-year earnings at consumer finance services reached Dollars 193.5m, up
from Dollars 175m in 1991.
Profits from insurance services in the fourth quarter rose 19 per cent to
Dollars 46.8m, taking the division's annual profits to Dollars 187.3m,
compared with Dollars 174.8m in 1991.
Sales of new life insurance remained flat, but mutual fund sales soared in
the final three months of the year, boosting total sales for the year to
Dollars 1.1bn, up 36 per cent on 1991.
Corporate expenses dropped sharply in the quarter, falling from Dollars
16.8m a year ago to Dollars 6.7m, thanks primarily to low US interest rates,
which reduced the cost of Primerica's debt. Overall, expenses in 1992 fell
51 per cent to Dollars 48.2m.
Primerica also said yesterday it planned to take a charge of about Dollars
15m in the first quarter of this year to cover the costs of adopting new
accounting procedures relating to post-retirement benefits.
</TEXT>
