<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Pounds 200m donation by Sainsbury chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES, Consumer Industries Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR David Sainsbury, chairman of supermarket chain J. Sainsbury and one of
Britain's richest men, has given shares in the company worth Pounds 200m to
the Gatsby Charitable Foundation, a grant-making trust which he set up and
has funded since 1967.
The donation, from Mr Sainsbury's personal holding, is believed to be by far
the largest UK charitable contribution by a private individual in recent
times. It was described as 'a staggering sum' by the Charities Aid
Foundation, which monitors charity finances.
The Gatsby Foundation disbursed about Pounds 15m last year, making it
Britain's third largest grant-giving trust measured by spending. Yesterday's
donation of 35.6m J. Sainsbury ordinary shares - roughly 2 per cent of the
company's equity - will increase its capital to about Pounds 500m.
Income from the donation will finance the foundation's existing commitments,
the cost of which exceeded its revenues in recent years. Until now, the
shortfall was made good by periodic contributions by Mr Sainsbury.
The trust, named after F. Scott Fitzgerald's novel The Great Gatsby - the
tragic tale of an ostentatious American parvenu with a mysterious past -
finances a wide range of activities close to the 52-year-old Mr Sainsbury's
personal interests.
They include management and technical education, African development
programmes, support for disadvantaged children, economic and business
research, healthcare and plant science. The trust is a leading supporter of
the Centre for Business Strategy at the London Business School, where Mr
Sainsbury is chairman of the board of governors.
The trust is the largest of several charitable organisations founded by
members of the Sainsbury family, which have total assets of about Pounds
1bn. Three of Mr Sainsbury's cousins helped finance a new wing for the
National Gallery in the late 1980s.
The Gatsby Foundation says it will retain the shares as an investment. They
currently pay an annual dividend of about Pounds 4m.
The arrangement will help to maintain effective control of the publicly
quoted company by family members, who together control directly and
indirectly about 42 per cent of its shares.
Mr Sainsbury will remain the wealthiest member of the family with a holding
of 312.5m shares after the donation.
J. Sainsbury's shares closed yesterday at 563p, up 1p.
</TEXT>
