<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Europe on the Brink (BBC 2, 7.45) looks like an expensive enterprise, with
presenter Francine Stock wafting around Europe in search of things to come.
Part one got off to a rather slow start last week, with the worthies of
Watlington on Remembrance Sunday burbling away about what it means to be
British. However, once we got to the experts' views and predictions, the
programme improved and was notably good, if hair-raising, about immigration.
This week's investigation focusses on the long-term economic prospects for
Europe weighed against America and South-east Asia.
Human nature being what it is, I am willing to bet that attendance figures
at London Zoo have been given a fillip by the recent episode of the poor man
who carried an armful of dead chickens into the lions' den and was mauled
for his pains.
The Ark (BBC 2, 9.25) is the first of no less than four documentaries about
the parlous state of London Zoo and the new management's plans to save the
rats - not to mention all the other hapless beasts - stuck on the sinking
ship.
