<TEXT>
COSTS AT British Nuclear Fuels' controversial Thorp plant at Sellafield
could soar by 'several hundred million pounds' in the first decade of
operation, jeopardising its economic basis, a report commissioned by the
environmental campaign group Greenpeace said yesterday, Bronwen Maddox
writes.
The new attack comes during a fierce debate about whether the plant for
reprocessing 'spent' or used nuclear fuel, which has taken Pounds 2.8bn and
nearly 10 years to build, should start operation.
A government inquiry is considering whether the economic, environmental and
political reasons for reprocessing have changed so much since the plant got
the go-ahead that it should become a white elephant.
BNF said that the figures were 'pure speculation'.
