<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Scottish reform costings disputed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT claims that its proposed reform of local government in Scotland
would lead to large cost savings have been challenged by Strathclyde
regional council, Scotland's largest local authority and the one most likely
to disappear if the reform goes ahead.
A council working party says savings would be much less - and transitional
costs far higher - than consultants Touche Ross calculated in a study for
the Scottish Office,
A Scottish Office green paper published in October proposes replacing the
nine regional councils, 53 district councils and three unitary island
councils with a single-tier structure. It made calculations on options
involving 15, 24, 35 and 51 unitary authorities.
Touche Ross said a 15-council structure would save Pounds 192m a year, 24
would save Pounds 120m, and 35 would save Pounds 55m. A 51-council
arrangement would cost Pounds 58m more.
Strathclyde says that reform would not lead to the big reduction in planning
and economic development costs envisaged by Touche Ross, and that savings in
central support services are overestimated. It says annual savings would
occur only if the government chose the 15-council model and would then only
amount to Pounds 71m. The other three models would produce higher annual
costs, with the 51-council structure costing Pounds 175m more.
The council says the consultants underestimated transitional costs,
including redundancy and residuary bodies' costs, and overestimated revenue
from property disposals.
Strathclyde says the transitional costs for 15 councils would be Pounds 333m
against the government estimate of Pounds 215m; for 24 councils it would be
Pounds 439m against Pounds 195m; for 35 councils it would be Pounds 476m
against Pounds 175m; and for 51 councils it would be Pounds 484m against
Pounds 159m.
</TEXT>
