<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Clause four returns to opposition
agenda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR'S most sacred cow - the controversial clause four of its
constitution, widely interpreted as a commitment to state-ownership - is
soon to be drawn into the increasingly vocal and public debate over the
party's economic and industrial policies.
In spite of clear reluctance from the leadership to hold a potentially
explosive discussion of the clause, Mr Jack Straw is to publish a pamphlet
next month putting the case for its terms to be reworded.
Last week the shadow local government minister made his first tentative
attempt to put reform on the agenda by presenting his conclusions to a
meeting of the Tribune group - the soft-left grouping of the parliamentary
party.
Next month the Fabian Society will join the debate when it publishes a new
model constitution for the party that is expected to drop the clause in
favour of a new statement of essential aims and values.
However, only a week ago, Mr John Smith, the party leader, repeated his
scepticism over the value of a debate, telling Sir David Frost in a BBC
interview that it was a 'theological' issue of little importance on
electors' doorsteps.
Mr Straw nonetheless has indicated to shadow cabinet colleagues that he
disagrees with this view. He says that, while the clause itself may not be
raised, there is plenty of doorstep evidence that Labour is still perceived
as the party of nationalisation.
The clause, drawn up 75 years ago by Sidney Webb, led to a fierce split in
the party in the 1950s when Hugh Gaitskell, then leader, argued vigorously
for its abandonment against strong and ultimately successful opposition.
The clause's most contentious paragraph reads: 'To secure for the workers by
hand or by brain the full fruits of their industry and the most equitable
distribution thereof that may be possible upon the basis of the common
ownership of the means of production, distribution and exchange . . . '
Defenders of the wording say that it is subject to wide-ranging
interpretation and does not represent a blanket commitment to state
ownership.
While some at last Wednesday's Tribune group meeting suggested that an open
debate could add a useful creative spur to reassessing Labour's goals,
others warned that it could be misinterpreted as the party abandoning its
core beliefs and 'throwing the baby out with the bathwater'.
Mr Straw yesterday said Labour should advocate a substantial scaling-down of
the British monarchy along the lines of the Dutch or Scandinavian models. He
told his Blackburn constituency that the current royal system 'with its
large number of participants and its emphasis on showbusiness has little
serious future'.
