<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour split over Maastricht
tactics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN EMERGING split in Labour ranks over tactics on the Maastricht bill has
given a boost to the government's hopes of defeating Tory opponents of the
treaty.
As government business managers gambled successfully last night on a vote to
force debate beyond 10pm, it emerged that prominent Labour pro-Europeans
have challenged their leadership's official policy of relentless tactical
opposition. Until now, Labour policy has been to join with Tory Euro-rebels
to oppose 'closure' motions that limit debate on hundreds of wrecking
amendments, in order to maximise disruption to the government's programme of
business.
But a number of pro-European Labour MPs are now warning that the party's
tactics risk undermining its European credentials while offering little
prospect of embarrassing the government. The divisions are expected to
emerge publicly tomorrow at a meeting of the parliamentary Labour party.
In last night's vote on whether to press on with the debate, Labour again
opposed the government motion on the grounds that 'it is up to the
government to get its business through'.
But the support of all but one Liberal Democrat MP helped to ensure that the
government won the day by a margin of 33 votes (304-271). This left it free
to continue considering the bill into the night rather than calling a halt
to proceedings at 10pm.
Having made its point, the government moved just before midnight that the
debate on a group of amendments on industrial and commercial issues be
brought to a close. It won this 'closure' by a commanding majority of 238
votes (299-61).
Since Labour had made clear it would advise its MPs not to support the
substance of the first of this group of amendments if it came to a vote,
debate then moved to consideration of transport and energy issues into the
small hours.
Skilful government handling of the bill and the tacit support of smaller
parties have now allowed the government to win closure motions on three of
the 25 groups of amendments which must be debated in the committee stage -
with the transport and energy group representing the fourth.
The legislation is due to return to the Commons today for the second of
three consecutive days of detailed debate in its committee stage,
More than 85 Labour MPs last month signed a motion calling for the 'rapid
completion' of the treaty's ratification. Many of them now want the party
leadership to quietly abstain on closure motions as long as reasonable
parliamentary time is allocated.
The pro-European MPs believe that they can rely on the support of less
committed colleagues who have become exasperated at being forced to remain
constantly in the Commons simply to vote against closure motions.
</TEXT>
