<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Arrears of VAT rising, MPs told
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ARREARS OF value added tax have continued to rise in the past few months,
Sir Brian Unwin, chairman of the Customs and Excise department, said
yesterday.
Average daily arrears as a proportion of tax liabilities rose to 4.5 per
cent by November last year against 4.4 per cent 12 months previously and a
target of 3.8 per cent, Sir Brian told the Commons' public accounts
committee.
But he stressed that default surcharges levied against traders who
consistently did not pay had fallen since the year end from Pounds 132m to
Pounds 125m.
Half of the outstanding amounts were from traders which had gone bankrupt
and much of the remainder related to amounts of less than Pounds 200 each,
which were uneconomic to collect.
He told MPs that 2,200 jobs in the department would be subject to market
testing in the current year. There would be no testing in core functions
such as policy advice, tax assessment and determination of liability.
Debt collection would be subject to market testing, but Sir Brian said
careful controls would be installed by local offices to ensure there were no
risks of breaching confidentiality or generating conflicts of interest among
contractors.
He said the changes brought about in VAT administration by the creation of
the single European market should not increase collection costs, but might
increase fraud.
</TEXT>
