<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Businessmen back PM on team for
India
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRIALISTS yesterday endorsed the prime minister's decision to take
senior businessmen on his India trip next week - a move described from
Downing Street as part of efforts to create jobs and promote co-operation
between Whitehall and industry.
Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the Confederation of British Industry,
who will be in the delegation, hailed the trip as symbolic while others said
prime ministerial involvement could help speed decision-making in India.
'To find a bit of prime ministerial time spent on promoting exports in a
very large but difficult market is something which cheers people up,' Mr
Davies said.
Businessmen from many of Britain's largest companies will accompany Mr
Major, who is travelling at the invitation of the Indian government.
Although not unprecedented, it is rare for prime ministers to take
businessmen on foreign trips.
The CBI told Mr Major at the end of last year that export promotion trips
should be higher on his agenda. The business leaders are expected to meet
counterparts in the country - and then report back to Mr Major and the
Indian prime minster.
If successful, Mr Major may consider taking businessmen on his other
overseas trips.
Mr Robert Evans, chairman of British Gas and a member of the delegation,
said the prime minister's decision was a 'tangible expression' of the
government's willingness to work with industry. British Gas is involved in
several large projects in India including schemes in Delhi, Bombay and
Calcutta.
British Aerospace, whose chief executive Mr Dick Evans is going, said the
trip reinforced the seriousness with which UK companies took relations with
India, Britain's 20th largest export market.
The other industrialists are: Sir Brian Shaw, chairman, ANZ Grindlays Bank;
Mr Terry Harrison, chief executive of Rolls-Royce; Mr Norman Davis,
director, British American Tobacco; Mr Brian Baldock, deputy chairman,
Guinness; Mr Peter Grant, chairman, Sun Life Assurance Society; Mr Philip
Daubeney, head of African and eastern region, ICI; Mr Norman Hawkins,
Cadbury Schweppes; Mr Patrick MacDougall, chairman, Chartered West; Mr
Philip Hills, executive director, Samuel Montagu; Mr G. Douglas Gadd,
chairman, GEC Alsthom; Mr Graham Hadley, executive director, National Power;
Mr Richard Reynolds, chairman, GPT; Mr Roger Mabey, managing director, Bovis
International; Mr Andrew Cummins, Inchcape.
</TEXT>
