<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Flats face dearer terror insurance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY OWNERS of flats in areas judged by insurers to be vulnerable to
terrorist attack could face sizeable increases in insurance premiums.
The increase, which could be up to Pounds 180 a year for a flat worth Pounds
200,000, may be necessary because insurers want to bring large blocks of
flats into a pool to cover terrorist damage, financed by a special charge on
policyholders.
The proposal is on the agenda at a meeting this week at which the
Association of British Insurers and the Department of Trade and Industry
will discuss details of how the pool will work. Insurers agreed last month
to establish the pool after the government said it would provide reinsurance
cover.  Following losses of Pounds 800m from an IRA bomb attack in April,
insurers announced in November that cover against terrorism would no longer
be made automatically to owners of commercial property.
It had been assumed that cover for residential properties would be
unaffected. Mr Tony Baker of the Association of British Insurers said,
however: 'Insurance companies want flats to be in the pool. They can't take
them on their own books.'
Mr Baker said yesterday that some leaseholders could be affected where the
freehold of their building was owned by an outside landowner.
Commercial policyholders will pay voluntary levies on top of existing
premiums to obtain cover through the terrorism pool. These levies will vary
according to the location and value of properties.
It is understood that up to Pounds 5m, most policyholders would face
increases of between 0.018 per cent and 0.09 per cent of the value of the
property depending on its location.
The rate would fall progressively to between 0.007 per cent and 0.023 per
cent for properties valued in excess of Pounds 500m.
Other issues on the agenda will include the liabilities of insurance
companies for any terrorism claims on policies bought before the exclusion
clause was introduced but which will remain in force until later this year.
Meanwhile, an industrial risk manager suggested that the charges for
properties based in central London were 'excessively penal'. Mr Alan Fleming
of the Association of Insurance and Risk Managers in Industry and Commerce,
which represents more than 300 companies, suggested the cost of the scheme
should be spread more widely.
</TEXT>
