<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Delay for equality in senior jobs forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOMEN will need at least 25 years to achieve equality in British management
according to Lady Howe, who chairs Opportunity 2000, the private-sector
initiative to promote the position of women in industry.
Lady Howe, speaking at the launch of an initiative to promote flexible
working among managers, was responding to critics of Opportunity 2000 who
say it has been insufficiently forceful in changing attitudes.
She said attitudes were gradually changing and 'macho' management was
becoming rarer - but she added that it would still take 25 years for women
to achieve equality with men.
A survey on flexible work for managers found 76 per cent of respondents
cited childcare responsibilities as their reason for seeking part-time or
flexible work. The survey was sponsored by National Westminster Bank.
Mr Martin Gray, chief executive of the bank's branch business, said new ways
of working need not damage performance and that companies benefit from
retaining qualified staff. He said 1,200 staff and managers at NatWest
either work part-time, share a job or work from home, and that 120 people
had applied for the last management job that involved working from home.
Ms Helen Dawson of the Local Government Management Board warned that
momentum towards more flexible working in local government had been lost
because of pressures associated with contracting-out.
</TEXT>
