FT  19 JAN 93 / Recovery to UK hoteliers increases to 27.1 per cent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE proportion of UK hoteliers who think recovery has begun increased to
27.1 per cent in the last quarter of 1992 compared with 13 per cent in the
previous quarter according to a survey by leisure consultants Horwath,
Michael Skapinker writes.
Although 72.9 per cent said they did not think the hotel industry had begun
to recover, this compared with 87 per cent in the previous quarter.
The number of hoteliers who were optimistic about the first quarter of this
year rose from 32 per cent to 35 per cent, while the proportion who were
pessimistic fell to 40 per cent from 47 per cent.
