<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Xmas retail trade below estimates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LATE boost to retail trade in the last few days before Christmas failed to
lift December sales above levels of a year ago, the Confederation of British
Industry reports today.
The CBI distributive trades survey contradicts anecdotal evidence of a
pick-up to shop sales last month, showing instead that many retailers had a
disappointing Christmas.
Mr Nigel Whittaker, chairman of the CBI's distributive trades panel, said,
however, that the results were an improvement on recent months. Sales this
month were expected to be up on a year ago.
Sales are reported to have fallen on a year-on-year basis for three
successive months. In December the balance between retailers reporting an
increase in sales and those reporting a decrease was minus 4, compared with
plus 5 in December 1991. In November the balance was minus 9.
The CBI noted a marked discrepancy between the performance of big retailers,
which indicated that their sales were up, and small retailers - employing
fewer than 200 people - which did badly.
It also believes that consumers have become more discerning and may have
been waiting for the January sales before making significant purchases.
Specialist food shops, off-licences, bookshops, stationers and DIY retailers
were among those which suffered a particularly dismal month. Off-licences
said sales had declined significantly year-on-year for five successive
months.
Business was better for confectioners, tobacconists, newsagents, chemists
and clothing retailers, whose sales were higher than in December 1991. The
survey was conducted between December 16 and January 6. The CBI says its
findings suggest it is too early to talk of a sustained recovery in consumer
spending.
Mr Whittaker said: 'Consumers are cautious . . . The cuts in interest rates
in the autumn have not yet had their full impact on consumer spending.'
Economists expect official figures due tomorrow to show a small increase on
the month, but a more substantial rise - about 2 per cent - on the year.
The CBI reported that motor trades had the best month in December, with
sales increasing against expectations. Although sales for the time of year
continued to be poor, they improved on November, with sales of vehicles
increasing and sales of parts and accessories falling.
Wholesalers reported a year-on-year decline in sales for the third
successive month. The survey said they were able to reduce stocks in
December following cuts in orders placed with suppliers.
