<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Key posts for rail sell-off are filled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yes-terday chose a lawyer and a former merchant banker for
two positions at the centre of its plans for implementing the privatisation
of British Rail.
They are Mr John Swift QC, an expert in competition law who is to become the
rail regulator, and Mr Roger Salmon, a former director at merchant bank NM
Rothschild who is to become director of passenger rail franchising.
Mr Swift, 52, will play a key role, ensuring that train operators -
passenger and freight - get fair access to the railway tracks at an
acceptable price. He will also be responsible for protecting rail
passengers' interests.
Mr Salmon, 46, who is now chairman of Cuff and Co, a family business, will
be responsible for franchising private-sector companies to take over the
operation of BR's passenger services and making sure they fulfil their
obligations once the franchises are awarded.
The latest appointments follow the government's decision last month to
install Mr Bob Horton, former chairman and chief executive of British
Petroleum, as vice-chairman of BR with special responsibility for setting up
Railtrack, the state-owned authority that will own BR's tracks.
Completion of these appointments emphasises the government's determination
to press on with rail privatisation in spite of sharp criticism of its plans
from the rail lobby, opposition parties and some Conservatives.
The last obstacle to the introduction of the necessary legislation appeared
to have been cleared yesterday when the paving bill completed its passage in
the Lords.
That means the government is on course to introduce the privatisation
legislation, known as the Railways Bill, to the Commons on Thurs-day.
Mr Robert Adley, chairman of the Commons transport committee which is
hearing evidence on the government's plans, intends to anticipate the bill
tomorrow by publishing an interim report of the committee's findings.
Mr Adley, a Conservative backbencher and railway enthusiast, has made no
secret of his hostility to the government's proposals. The report is,
however, expected to adopt a measured tone.
</TEXT>
