<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Ministers see dentist pay review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OPTIONS ON how dentists should be paid, ranging from tinkering with the
much-criticised system to a radical restructuring of the dental health
service, were presented to ministers yesterday.
The review of dentists' remuneration, which was launched by the government
last July to defuse a crisis that led to threats to leave the health service
and a vote to stop taking new NHS patients, makes no recommendations but
sets out possible improvements.
Every dentist will receive a copy of the report and there will be a long
consultation before ministers decide how to proceed. It appears that the
setting up of the review, which was chaired by Sir Kenneth Bloomfield,
former head of the Civil Service in Northern Ireland, has helped to defuse
the dispute between dentists and the government.
Dr Brian Mawhinney, health minister, said after receiving the report
yesterday that in the past six months there had been a net loss of only 15
dentists in the health service. 'There was considerable unhappiness (at the
cut in fees), but those who suggested a lot of dentists would behave
irresponsibly have been proved wrong,' he said.
The review has also underlined the lack of consensus within the dental
profession and outside on what should be done to upgrade the service and
make it more cost effective.
The only agreement seems to be that the status quo is unsatisfactory.
The options presented by Sir Kenneth include relatively minor changes to the
complex system, under which the country's 18,000 dentists are paid in the
form of reimbursement for practice expenses, fees for specific treatment,
and bulk payments for the number of patients signed up.
Radical reforms might include limiting the treatment available under the
health service, or further restricting those eligible for free or subsidised
treatment. The report favours maintaining free treatment for children, but
not necessarily for all pregnant women.
The report says that 'a greater concentration of available resources on
providing a smaller number of treatments could (subject to proper controls)
lead to a desirable shift in emphasis from quantity to quality'.
Fundamental Review of Dental Remuneration, Department of Health, 79
Whitehall, London SW1A 2NS.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
