<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 93 / Moslem-Croat clash puts pact at risk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fighting between Moslems and Croats, theoretically allies in the war against
Serbs, intensified in Bosnia-Hercegovina yesterday, overshadowing a crucial
Bosnian Serb vote due today on an internationally brokered peace plan for
Bosnia, writes Robert Mauthner.
The battle around Gornji Vakuf, a town in south-west Hercegovina near the
Adriatic, appears to have been provoked by the Geneva peace process itself,
particularly the map tabled by the international mediators, Mr Cyrus Vance
and Lord Owen.
Bosnian Croatian forces have attempted to consolidate their positions in
areas designated as Croat-controlled on the map which divides the proposed
future Bosnian state into 10 semi-autonomous provinces.
