<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / BA close to revised deal for a 20% holding in USAir
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Airways is expected shortly to announce a revised partnership deal
with USAir, the sixth largest US carrier.
The companies could unveil a deal this week, following the inauguration on
Wednesday of President Bill Clinton, who criticised the original proposal
during his election campaign.
That partnership agreement - blocked in December by a US-UK government
dispute over liberalising air services between the two countries - would
have given BA a 44 per cent stake in USAir for Dollars 750m (Pounds 488m).
The new deal would give BA about 20 per cent, for an investment of Dollars
340m, and voting rights of about 20 per cent. BA, which last week apologised
for waging a 'dirty tricks' campaign against rival Virgin Atlantic and paid
out about Pounds 3.6m in damages and costs, confirmed yesterday that
discussions were continuing with USAir on some form of alliance. BA is
believed to have dropped its demand for a right of veto on important
spending decisions - a factor which hindered approval of the original
agreement.
The new deal stands a better chance of being cleared by the US authorities
than the earlier, more ambitious proposal. In pitching for a stake and
voting rights of less than 25 per cent, BA will hope the US Department of
Transportation will nod the deal through. In its initial proposal, BA argued
that its stake of 44 per cent would only carry a 21 per cent voting right,
but big US carriers objected.
These US carriers may well continue their campaign against the revised deal.
American, United, and Delta put intense pressure on the US government to
insist the UK opened up London's Heathrow Airport to more US airline
services in return for approving the original deal.
United said yesterday it could not comment on a new BA deal without knowing
the details. It said it saw any agreement between BA and USAir as a chance
for the UK and US to develop more liberal open skies policies.
BA and USAir would become closely integrated, carrying out joint marketing.
BA sees the alliance as the means to take advantage of deregulating markets
in Europe and across the Atlantic, giving it unrivalled access to the US
east coast compared with European competitors.
Virgin to press its case, Page 6
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Airways.
    USAir Group Inc.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
