<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / Observer: Yes and no
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
It is hard to believe that the poor old NatWest bosses involved in the Blue
Arrow affair were the only bankers who had trouble understanding what a bank
supervisor is saying, let alone thinking.
Fortunately, help is at hand. The Old Lady, the house magazine of the Bank
of England, has a few tips on how to get the most out of a conversation with
a bank supervisor. Rule number one: a banking supervisor never says yes.
Rather, he 'has no objection' to a particular suggestion - or,
alternatively, he 'takes comfort' from what is proposed.
It is also important to realise that a banking supervisor never says no. He
simply confines himself to expressing the fact that he is uncomfortable.
</TEXT>
